"sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "phil", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "gregg wallace", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "melissa mead", "sentiment": "none"}], "locations": [{"name": "hollyoaks", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "googleí", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "england", "sentiment": "none"}], "organizations": [{"name": "a&e", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "google", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "nhs", "sentiment": "none"}]}, "highlightText": "", "language": "english", "persons": [], "text": "Holly was left in tears (Picture: ITV) Holly Willoughby was left in tears and apologising to This Morning viewers on Thursday after meeting a mum whose baby son died of sepsis after ’16 mistakes’ by the NHS.\nGregg Wallace reveals that he met his wife Anne-Marie on Twitter Holly broke down after meeting Melissa Mead, a campaigner who was on the show to raise awareness following the death of her son William from the condition 2014.\nAs Melissa told her story and revealed that they keep some of the ashes in a teddy bear so that they can keep him with them, Holly dabbed a tissue at her eyes at Melissa spoke of her ‘content’ and ‘perfect’ son, and revealed that she was ‘blessed that he picked me to be his mum’.\nHolly apologised for her tears (Picture: ITV) Holly and Phil with Melissa Mead (Picture: ITV) Holly’s co-host Phillip Schofield took over the interview as Holly wept, and as he wrapped up the segment, Holly apologised.\n‘I’m sorry,’ she told viewers several times as Phil spoke, before getting up to give Melissa a hug off-camera.\n&&&&& To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that supports HTML5 video \nWilliam had a persistent cough for several weeks before his parents Melissa and Paul were told it was a viral infection, however as the symptoms got worse and he developed a high fever, they visited an emergency doctor.\nThe family were then sent home, and three days later William died of blood poisoning following the infection, 16 hours after their last call to the non-emergency line 111.\n<img data-attachment-id=\"5644897\" data-permalink=\"http://metro.co.uk/?attachment_id=5644897\" data-orig-file=\"https://metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/ad_194363596.jpg?quality=80&strip=all&strip=all\" data-orig-size=\"1406,2500\" data-comments-opened=\"0\" data-image-meta=\"{\"aperture\":\"0\",\"credit\":\"SWNS.com\",\"camera\":\"\",\"caption\":\"William Mead who died after contracting an infection. See SWNS story; A mother whose baby son died after NHS helpline blunders has said she \\u00ebcould have got more information from Google\\u00ed. Melissa Mead, 28, lost her one-year-old son William to blood poisoning after a 111 operator with no medical training instructed her to give him Calpol. The adviser made one incorrect decision after another trying to follow the \\u00ebpathway\\u00ed laid down by the 111 service\\u00eds computer. William could have survived if he had been admitted immediately to hospital with a lung abscess caused by a bacterial infection.\",\"created_timestamp\":\"0\",\"copyright\":\"\",\"focal_length\":\"0\",\"iso\":\"0\",\"shutter_speed\":\"0\",\"title\":\"\",\"orientation\":\"0\"}\" data-image-title=\"AD_194363596.jpg\" data-image-description=\"<p>William Mead who died after contracting an infection. See SWNS story; A mother whose baby son died after NHS helpline blunders has said she ëcould have got more information from Googleí. Melissa Mead, 28, lost her one-year-old son William to blood poisoning after a 111 operator with no medical training instructed her to give him Calpol. The adviser made one incorrect decision after another trying to follow the ëpathwayí laid down by the 111 serviceís computer. William could have survived if he had been admitted immediately to hospital with a lung abscess caused by a bacterial infection.</p> \" data-medium-file=\"https://metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/ad_194363596.jpg?quality=80&strip=all&w=169&strip=all\" data-large-file=\"https://metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/ad_194363596.jpg?quality=80&strip=all&w=576&strip=all\" class=\"img-align-none wp-image-5644897 size-full\" src=\"https://metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/ad_194363596.jpg?quality=80&strip=all&strip=all\" alt=\"William Mead who died after contracting an infection. See SWNS story; A mother whose baby son died after NHS helpline blunders has said she ëcould have got more information from Googleí. Melissa Mead, 28, lost her one-year-old son William to blood poisoning after a 111 operator with no medical training instructed her to give him Calpol. The adviser made one incorrect decision after another trying to follow the ëpathwayí laid down by the 111 serviceís computer. William could have survived if he had been admitted immediately to hospital with a lung abscess caused by a bacterial infection.\" width=\"1024\" height=\"1821\" /></div><figcaption>William died when he was 12 months old (Picture: SWNS)</figcaption></figure> It later emerged that NHS failings led to his death after neither the GP, A&E department nor 111 call handlers recognised the sepsis symptons.\nAt a memorial service on Saturday, Jeremy Hunt, the Health Secretary, publicly apologised to the family, admitting that the government and the NHS let them down.\n<figure class=\"alignnone img-container shareable-item\" style=\"max-width:620px\"><div class=\"img-wrap\"><a id=\"item-attachment_5644898\" class=\"anchor\"></a><div class=\"item-share-buttons item-share\"><a class=\"share-item share-item-facebook btn\" title=\"Share this on Facebook\" data-track=\"share-item-facebook\"><span class=\"icon icon-facebook\"></span></a><a class=\"share-item share-item-twitter btn\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Share this on Twitter\" data-track=\"share-item-twitter\"><span class=\"icon icon-twitter\"></span></a><a class=\"share-item share-item-pinterest btn\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Share this on Pinterest\" data-track=\"share-item-pinterest\"><span class=\"icon icon-pinterest\"></span></a></div><img data-attachment-id=\"5644898\" data-permalink=\"http://metro.co.uk/?attachment_id=5644898\" data-orig-file=\"https://metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/ad_194363598.jpg?quality=80&strip=all&strip=all\" data-orig-size=\"896,1280\" data-comments-opened=\"0\" data-image-meta=\"{\"aperture\":\"0\",\"credit\":\"SWNS.com\",\"camera\":\"\",\"caption\":\"William Mead who died after contracting an infection. See SWNS story; A mother whose baby son died after NHS helpline blunders has said she \\u00ebcould have got more information from Google\\u00ed. Melissa Mead, 28, lost her one-year-old son William to blood poisoning after a 111 operator with no medical training instructed her to give him Calpol. The adviser made one incorrect decision after another trying to follow the \\u00ebpathway\\u00ed laid down by the 111 service\\u00eds computer. William could have survived if he had been admitted immediately to hospital with a lung abscess caused by a bacterial infection.\",\"created_timestamp\":\"0\",\"copyright\":\"\",\"focal_length\":\"0\",\"iso\":\"0\",\"shutter_speed\":\"0\",\"title\":\"\",\"orientation\":\"0\"}\" data-image-title=\"AD_194363598.jpg\" data-image-description=\"<p>William Mead who died after contracting an infection. See SWNS story; A mother whose baby son died after NHS helpline blunders has said she ëcould have got more information from Googleí. Melissa Mead, 28, lost her one-year-old son William to blood poisoning after a 111 operator with no medical training instructed her to give him Calpol. The adviser made one incorrect decision after another trying to follow the ëpathwayí laid down by the 111 serviceís computer. William could have survived if he had been admitted immediately to hospital with a lung abscess caused by a bacterial infection.</p> \" data-medium-file=\"https://metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/ad_194363598.jpg?quality=80&strip=all&w=210&strip=all\" data-large-file=\"https://metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/ad_194363598.jpg?quality=80&strip=all&w=717&strip=all\" class=\"img-align-none size-full wp-image-5644898\" src=\"https://metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/ad_194363598.jpg?quality=80&strip=all&strip=all\" alt=\"William Mead who died after contracting an infection. See SWNS story; A mother whose baby son died after NHS helpline blunders has said she ëcould have got more information from Googleí. Melissa Mead, 28, lost her one-year-old son William to blood poisoning after a 111 operator with no medical training instructed her to give him Calpol. The adviser made one incorrect decision after another trying to follow the ëpathwayí laid down by the 111 serviceís computer. William could have survived if he had been admitted immediately to hospital with a lung abscess caused by a bacterial infection.\" width=\"896\" height=\"1280\" /></div><figcaption>William Mead (Picture: SWNS)</figcaption></figure> ‘This weekend, William should have been enjoying beautiful Cornish sunshine with his parents, and because, we, I as Health Secretary, the government, the NHS, let down William, Paul, and Melissa, we didn’t spot his sepsis before it was too late,’ he said, in an unprecedented manner.\n<aside class=\"zone-post-strip\"><h3>More: <a href=\"https://metrouk2.wordpress.com/entertainment/tv/\" data-track=\"zone-post-strip-more\">TV</a></h3><div class=\"zopo-item\"><a href=\"http://metro.co.uk/2017/03/30/another-guest-has-proposed-on-the-jeremy-kyle-show-and-viewers-werent-having-it-6542972\" class=\"zopo-link\" data-track=\"zone-post-strip-item\" data-track-destination=\"6542972\"><img src=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhEAAJAIAAAP///wAAACH5BAE L QAAkAAAIKhI+py+0Po5yUFQA7\" data-src=\"http://i2.wp.com/metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2017/03/jeremy-kyle-proposal.jpg?crop=90px%2C0px%2C530px%2C397px&resize=480%2C360&quality=80&strip=all&ssl=1&w=170&h=128\" data-aspect=\"1. \" data-rewritten=\"false\" width=\"170\" height=\"128\" /><span class=\"zopo-title-text\">Another guest has proposed on The Jeremy Kyle Show and viewers weren't having it</span>\n</a></div><div class=\"zopo-item\"><a href=\"http://metro.co.uk/2017/03/30/hollyoaks-spoilers-video-preview-reveals-ste-hay-and-harry-thompson-are-both-arrested-for-amy-barnes-murder-6542870\" class=\"zopo-link\" data-track=\"zone-post-strip-item\" data-track-destination=\"6542870\"><img src=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhEAAJAIAAAP///wAAACH5BAE L QAAkAAAIKhI+py+0Po5yUFQA7\" data-src=\"http://i1.wp.com/metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2017/03/ste.jpg?crop=240px%2C0px%2C1440px%2C1080px&resize=480%2C360&quality=80&strip=all&ssl=1&w=170&h=128\" data-aspect=\"1. \" data-rewritten=\"false\" width=\"170\" height=\"128\" /><span class=\"zopo-title-text\">Ste and Harry are both arrested over Amy's murder in Hollyoaks tonight</span>\n</a></div><div class=\"zopo-item\"><a href=\"http://metro.co.uk/2017/03/30/12-stars-you-never-knew-began-their-careers-on-channel-5-6511933\" class=\"zopo-link\" data-track=\"zone-post-strip-item\" data-track-destination=\"6511933\"><img src=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhEAAJAIAAAP///wAAACH5BAE L QAAkAAAIKhI+py+0Po5yUFQA7\" data-src=\"http://i1.wp.com/metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2016/02/453777085.jpg?crop=331px%2C0px%2C3124px%2C2342px&resize=480%2C360&quality=80&strip=all&ssl=1&w=170&h=128\" data-aspect=\"1. \" data-rewritten=\"false\" width=\"170\" height=\"128\" /><span class=\"zopo-title-text\">12 stars whose careers began on Channel 5</span>\n</a></div></aside> <div class=\"metro-factbox full\"> <h3 class=\"metro-factbox-title grey exclamation\">What is Sepsis?</h3> <div class=\"metro-factbox-content grey\"></p> Sepsis is a rare but serious complication of an infection.\nWithout quick treatment, sepsis can lead to multiple organ failure and death.\nGo straight to A&E or call 999 if your child:\nlooks mottled, bluish or pale\nis very lethargic or difficult to wake\nfeels abnormally cold to touch\nis breathing very fast\nhas a rash that does not fade when you press it\nhas a fit or convulsion\nGet medical advice urgently from NHS 111 if your child has any of the symptoms listed below, is getting worse or is sicker than you’d expect (even if their temperature falls), trust your instincts and seek medical advice urgently from NHS 111.\nTemperature:\ntemperature over 38C in babies under three months\ntemperature over 39C in babies aged three to six months\nany high temperature in a child who cannot be encouraged to show interest in anything\nlow temperature (below 36C – check three times in a 10-minute period)\nBreathing:\nfinding it much harder to breathe than normal – looks like hard work\nmaking “grunting” noises with every breath\ncan’t say more than a few words at once (for older children who normally talk)\nbreathing that obviously “pauses”\nToilet/nappies:\nnot had a wee or wet nappy for 12 hours\nEating and drinking:\nnew baby under one month old with no interest in feeding\nnot drinking for more than eight hours (when awake)\nbile-stained (green), bloody or black vomit/sick\nActivity and body:\nsoft spot on a baby’s head is bulging\neyes look “sunken”\nchild cannot be encouraged to show interest in anything\nbaby is floppy\nweak, “whining” or continuous crying in a younger child\nolder child who’s confused\nnot responding or very irritable\nstiff neck, especially when trying to look up and down\nThere are around 123,000 cases of sepsis a year in England; sepsis kills 37,000 people more than breast, bowel and prostate cancer combined.\nVia <a href=\"http://www.nhs.uk/Conditions/Blood-poisoning/Pages/Introduction.aspx\">NHS</a>\n</div> </div> \n<span class=\"mor-link\">MORE: <a href=\"http://metro.co.uk/2016/10/24/what-is-sepsis-deadly-condition-kills-tens-of-thousands-every-year-6211793/\" data-track=\"article/in-content-link-6542976-1\" >What is sepsis? Deadly condition kills tens of thousands every year</a></span>\n<span class=\"mor-link\">MORE: <a href=\"http://metro.co.uk/2012/09/07/world-sepsis-day-launched-to-reduce-deaths-from-disease-that-kills-millions-567758/\" data-track=\"article/in-content-link-6542976-2\" >World Sepsis Day launched to reduce deaths from disease that kills millions</a></span>", "external_links": [], "published": "2017-03-30T18:51:00.000+03:00", "crawled": "2017-03-30T13:51:37.703+03:00", "highlightTitle": ""}